Day 4. RNASeq downsteam analysis, Part 2

by Zuguang Gu (z.gu@dkfz.de), 2017-12-13 21:05:43. The github repository for this material is at https://github.com/eilslabs/teaching.

We will use the three objects count, deseq2 and anno which have been generated on day 3. If you forget how to generate them, just run following code:

library(airway)  # load the airway package
data(airway)
count = assay(airway)

library(DESeq2)
deseq2 = vst(count)

anno = as.data.frame(colData(airway))
anno = anno[, c("cell", "dex")]

Differential expression analysis by classical statistical test

Generally, to compare two groups which are represented as two numeric vectors, we use t-test if we assume the data follows a normal distribution or a rank-based test like Wilcoxon test if we test it non-parametricly (here non-parametric means no prior statistical distribution is assumed for the data).

First we test whether the 3rd gene is differentially expressed between trt and untrt conditions.

# recall we need to use the normalized values to compare between samples
x = deseq2[3, ]
# extract the expression values in "trt" group
x1 = x[anno$dex == "trt"]
# extract the expression values in "untrt" group
x2 = x[anno$dex == "untrt"]

t.test() function can be applied to x1 and x2 to perform t-test:

t.test(x1, x2)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x1 and x2
## t = 3.5933, df = 4.2276, p-value = 0.02084
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.04652325 0.33567163
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  9.227406  9.036308

We can see the p-value is significant (< 0.05), which means this gene is significantly differentially epxressed between trt and untrt groups.

We can confirm it by looking at the boxplot.

boxplot(list(trt = x1, untrt = x2))

The results returned by t.test() can be assigned to a variable.

test = t.test(x1, x2)

And the p-value can be obtained from test variable.

# e.g. the p-value
test$p.value
## [1] 0.02084481

Next we test differential expression of the 12th gene similarly by t-test.

x = deseq2[12, ]
x1 = x[anno$dex == "trt"]
x2 = x[anno$dex == "untrt"]
t.test(x1, x2)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x1 and x2
## t = -0.12009, df = 5.9992, p-value = 0.9083
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.8521257  0.7724008
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  11.40061  11.44047
boxplot(list(trt = x1, untrt = x2))

We can see this gene almost shows no difference between trt/untrt.

We can test these two genes by the non-parametric Wilcoxon rank-based test by the wilcox.test() function.

x = deseq2[3, ]
x1 = x[anno$dex == "trt"]
x2 = x[anno$dex == "untrt"]
wilcox.test(x1, x2)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test
## 
## data:  x1 and x2
## W = 16, p-value = 0.02857
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
x = deseq2[12, ]
x1 = x[anno$dex == "trt"]
x2 = x[anno$dex == "untrt"]
wilcox.test(x1, x2)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test
## 
## data:  x1 and x2
## W = 7, p-value = 0.8857
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

You may see the p-values are difference between different testing methods. This is what it should be because the p-value is always calculated from the distribution of the null hypothesis and different tests have different null hypothesis, however, the p-value should not differ too much.

For the complete gene expression data, we need to apply testing for all genes. We can do it in a for loop or simply use apply() function.

p_value_t_test = apply(deseq2, 1, function(x) {
    x1 = x[anno$dex == "trt"]
    x2 = x[anno$dex == "untrt"]
    if(length(unique(x1)) == 1 || length(unique(x2)) == 1) {
        return(NA)
    } else {
        t = t.test(x1, x2)
        return(t$p.value)
    }
})

If above code, the self-defined function will be applied to each row in deseq2 matrix.

For x1 and x2 which are involved in the t-test, both vectors should have at least two distinct values, and that is way we assign NA if x1 or x2 has no enough data points.

Here we dont suggest to use Wilcoxon test for this dataset because the number of data points in the two groups (which is 4) are too small.

Multiple testing

Each gene is applied by a test and has a p-value. The p-value means the probability that the data follows the null hypothesis. E.g. if a gene has a p-value of 0.01, it means the probability of saying trt/untrt has no difference is 0.01. Or in other words, the probability of the conclusion the gene is differentially expressed between trt/untrt is wrong is 0.01. (This explanation is not strictly correct, but you can understand like just like that.)

As long as the p-value is not exactly zero, there is always probability that the genes you call significantly differentially expressed are not true or they are false positives. Lets image a simple scenario. Assume you have 10000 genes and all genes have p-value of 0.01. Will you take all 10000 genes as differnetially expressed genes? We can simply calculate the probability of at least one false positive: 1-(1-0.01)^10000 which is almost 100% true. In other words, for these 10000 genes, there must be at least one gene which is false positive. Thus, we need to adjust the raw p-values to reduce false positives when you do more than one statistic test (or formally called mulitple testing).

There are several methods that you can check in the document of p.adjust() function. One of the most used method is called the BH method.

adjp = p.adjust(p_value_t_test, method = "BH")

Check how many genes have p-values < 0.05 and how many genes have adjusted p-values < 0.05.

sum(p_value_t_test < 0.05, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 4364
sum(adjp < 0.05, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 267

By looking these two numbers, you can have an impression of how many the false positives are there if you do not apply p-value adjustment.

Differential expression by DESeq2

When you do statistical test, there is always a null hypothesis (e.g.t-test assume the data follows a normal distribution). For RNASeq data which is count-based data, DESeq2 package provides a more proper test which is designed for count-based data.

Before we apply DESeq2 analysis, we need to convert anno$dex to a factor. Here levels of anno$dex is important for calculating log2 fold change. If levels == c("untrt", "trt"), a positive log2 fold change means the gene is highly expressed in trt group. Thus the log2 fold change is calculated as log2(trt/untrt).

anno$dex = factor(anno$dex, levels = c("untrt", "trt"))

Following code performs the DESeq2 differential expression analysis:

# construct the data structure for the analysis
dds = DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = count,
                             colData   = anno,
                             design    = ~ dex)
# perform the analysis
dds = DESeq(dds)
# retrieve the results
res = results(dds)
# convert to the data frame
res_dex = as.data.frame(res)
head(res_dex)
##                    baseMean log2FoldChange     lfcSE       stat     pvalue
## ENSG00000000003 708.6021697    -0.36076055 0.1648637 -2.1882354 0.02865246
## ENSG00000000005   0.0000000             NA        NA         NA         NA
## ENSG00000000419 520.2979006     0.20037122 0.0988954  2.0260923 0.04275533
## ENSG00000000457 237.1630368     0.03315858 0.1229655  0.2696575 0.78742375
## ENSG00000000460  57.9326331    -0.10169404 0.2614920 -0.3888992 0.69735068
## ENSG00000000938   0.3180984    -0.08980382 0.1614546 -0.5562173 0.57806230
##                      padj
## ENSG00000000003 0.1392880
## ENSG00000000005        NA
## ENSG00000000419 0.1830287
## ENSG00000000457 0.9306857
## ENSG00000000460 0.8956152
## ENSG00000000938        NA

When there is NA in the table, it means the counts for the gene are all (or majority) zero and not enough for the test.

The columns in res_dex are:

  • baseMean: the row means of the count table which is the mean expression level for genes across samples
  • log2FoldChange: log2 fold change between trt and untrt
  • lfsSE: standard error of the log2 fold change
  • stat: the statistics from the test
  • pvalue: raw p-values
  • padj: adjusted p-values

Check how many genes are significantly differentially expressed if we set the significance level to 0.05.

sum(res_dex$padj < 0.05, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 2699

We can check the overlap of the differential genes from DESeq2 method and t-test:

library(gplots) # run install.packages("gplots") if not installed
plot(venn(list(t_test = which(adjp < 0.05), deseq2 = which(res_dex$padj < 0.05))))

We can see the DESeq2 method is more powerful than the t-test because DESeq2 has a more proper null hypothesis or null distribution for testing.

In the DESeq2 results res_dex, there are several statistics which are important for interpretation of the results. We need baseMean to know the expression level of genes, we need log2FoldChange to know how much the gene is differentially expressed between the two groups, and we need padj to know which difference is significant. A so-called MA-plot can visualize these three statistics at a same time.

plot(log10(res_dex$baseMean + 1), res_dex$log2FoldChange, pch = 16, cex = 0.3, 
    col = ifelse(res_dex$padj < 0.05, "red", "#00000040"))

In the MA-plot, significant genes are marked as red points. From above plot, it generally shows when genes have lower expression, the log2 fold change should be higher to be called significant, and secondly, the majority of differential genes are intermeidately expressed (at around x = 3).

After we have a list of differential genes, we can visualize the expression of them as a heamtap.

library(ComplexHeatmap)
index_sig = which(res_dex$padj < 0.05)
mat = deseq2[index_sig, ]
mat_scaled = t(scale(t(mat)))
Heatmap(mat_scaled, name = "expr", show_row_names = FALSE,
    top_annotation = HeatmapAnnotation(df = anno, show_annotation_name = TRUE)
)

For showing the heamtap of differentially expressed genes, we usually use the matrix scaled by rows. You can compare to the original matrix:

Heatmap(mat, name = "expr", show_row_names = FALSE,
    top_annotation = HeatmapAnnotation(df = anno, show_annotation_name = TRUE)
)

Similarly, we can look for differentially expressed genes for different cell types:

dds = DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = count,
                             colData   = anno,
                             design    = ~ cell)  # <<== we change here
dds = DESeq(dds)
res = results(dds)
res_cell = as.data.frame(res)
# how many differentially expressed genes
sum(res_cell$padj < 0.05, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 416
index_sig = which(res_cell$padj < 0.05)
mat = deseq2[index_sig, ]
mat_scaled = t(scale(t(mat)))
Heatmap(mat_scaled, name = "expr", show_row_names = FALSE,
    top_annotation = HeatmapAnnotation(df = anno, show_annotation_name = TRUE)
)

Functional enrichment

Once we have a list of differetially expressed genes, the next step is always to look for the biological functions that the genes are enriched in.

Normally we use Fishers exact test to test the enrichment. Assume \(k_{10}\) is the number of differential genes, \(k_{01}\) is the number of genes annotated in a biological function (or called a term, which is normally from public database), \(k_{11}\) is the number of differential genes which have the biological function and \(k_{00}\) is the number of background genes (e.g.total number of human genes). Following 2x2 contingency table is constructed.

has function no function total
is diff k_11 k_10 - k_11 k_10
not diff k_01 - k_11 k_00 - k_01 - k_10 + k _11 k_00 - k_10
total k_01 k_00 - k_01 k_00

If differential genes are enriched in the biological function, \(k_{11}\) is significantly higher than if they are not enriched. Fishers exact test is designed to test this type of enrichment.

In R, we use clusterProfiler package (http://www.bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/html/clusterProfiler.html) to perform enrichment analysis. Install it if you havent had it yet:

source("https://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R")
biocLite("clusterProfiler")
biocLite("org.Hs.eg.db")

In following example, we enrich genes which are highly expressed in trt to biological functions.

library(clusterProfiler)
up_index = which(res_dex$padj < 0.05 & res_dex$log2FoldChange > 0)
up_genes = rownames(res_dex[up_index, ])
head(up_genes)
## [1] "ENSG00000002834" "ENSG00000003402" "ENSG00000003987" "ENSG00000004059"
## [5] "ENSG00000004700" "ENSG00000005007"

The biological terms (e.g. Gene Ontology terms or KEGG pathway terms) are always from public databases. To enrich differential genes to biological terms, we need to map genes to biological terms first. One of the most common problem is the inconsistency between gene IDs for differential genes and the gene IDs for genes in biological terms.

up_genes use Ensembl IDs as gene ID while for the Gene Ontology terms which we will use later, the gene IDs are NCBI Entrez IDs. First we need to convert Ensembl IDs to Entrez IDs.

clusterProfiler provides a bitr() function which is easy to convert between different gene ID types.

mapping = bitr(up_genes, fromType = "ENSEMBL", toType = "ENTREZID", OrgDb = "org.Hs.eg.db")
up_genes = unique(mapping[, 2])
head(up_genes)
## [1] "3927" "8837" "9108" "381"  "5965" "5976"

You may see there are warnings saying the mapping is not 100%. There are two reasons. First the genes in our analysis also contains non-protein coding genes which do not have a Entrez ID and the second reason is the mapping between different ID types in different public databases is normally not 100% match. But basically it wont affect the enrichment analysis.

Run enrichGO() to perfrom GO enrichment analysis. in OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db part, org.Hs.eg.db is a human gene database which is already processed by Bioconductor and ont controls the category of GO terms where BP correspond to biological functions, MF corresponds to molecular functions and CC corresponds to cellular components. Check the document of enrichGO() for more detailed explanation.

go = enrichGO(gene = up_genes, OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db, ont = "BP")

clusterProfiler package also provides functions to visualize the enrichment results. A very useful function is dotplot().

go = as.data.frame(go)

Exercise

task

Can you do GO and KEGG enrichment for the genes which are down-regulated in trt group and compare the enriched functions/pathways to those of the trt up-regulated genes?

Steps:

  1. get the gene list which are down-regulated in trt group
  2. convert to Entrez IDs
  3. do GO enrichment or KEGG enrichment
  4. extract the GO/KEGG ids by e.g. go$ID
  5. use venn() from gplots package to make Venn diagram

solution

down_index = which(res_dex$padj < 0.05 & res_dex$log2FoldChange < 0)
down_genes = rownames(res_dex[down_index, ])
mapping = bitr(down_genes, fromType = "ENSEMBL", toType = "ENTREZID", OrgDb = "org.Hs.eg.db")
down_genes = unique(mapping[, 2])
go_down = enrichGO(gene = down_genes, OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db, ont = "BP")
kegg_down = enrichKEGG(gene = down_genes, organism = 'hsa')

library(gplots)
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
venn(list(up = go$ID, down = go_down$ID))
title("GO, up vs down")
venn(list(up = kegg$ID, down = kegg_down$ID))
title("KEGG, up vs down")
